ce:section.ce:para:
We devised a colorimetric and fluorescent dual-mode method for isoniazid determination (Scheme 1
                        ). As showed in Fig. 2
                        -A, there was a broad absorption band between 250 nm and 450 nm in the UV spectrum of MnO2 nanosheets (absorber). The excitation and emission spectra of N-CDs (fluorescer), with peak at 350 nm and 440 nm respectively, both overlapped with the UV spectrum of MnO2 nanosheets. Therefore, the fluorescence of N-CDs was “turned off” due to inner filter effect. Isoniazid could destroy MnO2 nanosheets through redox reaction and “turned on” the fluorescence again. As depicted in Fig. 2-B, N-CDs showed high fluorescent intensity in aqueous solution. In the presence of MnO2 nanosheets, the fluorescent intensity slumped obviously. After the addition of isoniazid, the fluorescent intensity could recover to an extent, depending on the amount of isoniazid. There was no detectable intensity change in N-CDs/isoniazid solution, which proved that the recovery of the fluorescence came from the disintegration of MnO2 nanosheets. To confirm the mechanism was IFE instead of FRET (fluorescence resonance energy transfer), zeta potential analysis was then employed. MnO2 nanosheets showed a negative potential of around −36.2 mV and N-CDs of around −25.2 mV (Fig. 2-C), which suggested electrostatic repulsion prevent them from getting close to each other. Since FRET only occurs when the distance between the donor and acceptor are close enough for energy transfer, it indicates that the mechanism is not FRET. MnO2 nanosheets also showed catalytic activity (Fig. 2-D), it could oxidize TMB into blue oxTMB (with an absorption peak at 650 nm), causing color change in the solution. This can be used to indicate the concentration of MnO2 nanosheets and isoniazid. As the content of isoniazid increases, less TMB can be oxidized into oxTMB owing to the disintegration of MnO2 nanosheets.
